                <h2>Why Do Accounts Always "Step on Mines"</h2>
<p>Overseas advertising teams often experience this: ads are running well, then suddenly receive a platform notice about "account restrictions" or "ad disapprovals." After retrospectives, many discover the problems had early warning signs —素材文案未检查、落地页悄悄改了内容、投放地区政策悄悄更新……</p>
<p>Compliance inspection isn't about firefighting after problems occur; it should become a daily operational habit. This SOP breaks inspection into three levels: "10 minutes daily," "30 minutes weekly," and "1 hour monthly," enabling different team members to get started quickly.</p>
<h2>1. Pre-Inspection Preparation</h2>
<p>Before starting inspections, ensure you've completed:  </p>
<ol>
<li><strong>Compile account lists for all platforms</strong>, including account IDs, targeting regions, and business types</li>
<li><strong>Establish a violation records log</strong>, documenting reasons and remediation actions</li>
<li><strong>Subscribe to official platform policy update notifications</strong> to receive policy changes promptly</li>
<li><strong>Confirm contacts with legal/compliance departments</strong> for consultation when facing ambiguous situations</li>
</ol>
<blockquote>
<p>Core principle: Centralize information, maintain accessible records, keep communication channels open, and assign clear responsibilities.</p>
</blockquote>
<h2>2. Daily Inspection (10 Minutes)</h2>
<h3>Step 1: Check Account Status</h3>
<p>Open each platform's ad dashboard and browse in order:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Account health status</strong>: Any red warnings or restriction alerts</li>
<li><strong>Ad approval status</strong>: Any ads in "disapproved" status</li>
<li><strong>Spend anomalies</strong>: Today's spend deviation exceeding 50% from historical average</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 2: Review Notification Center</h3>
<p>This is the most overlooked but critical step. Open notifications to check:</p>
<ul>
<li>Platform policy update emails/inbox messages</li>
<li>Specific rejection reasons (usually with policy clause explanations)</li>
<li>Other account administrators' action records</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 3: Respond Quickly to Rejected Ads</h3>
<p>For ads marked "disapproved":</p>
<ol>
<li>Record rejection reasons</li>
<li>Modify creative or copy based on platform guidance</li>
<li>Resubmit after modifications</li>
<li>If disagreeing with the decision, submit appeal within the timeframe</li>
</ol>
<h3>Daily Inspection Checklist</h3>
<table>
<thead>
<tr>
<th>Item</th>
<th>Status</th>
<th>Notes</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td>Account status normal</td>
<td>✅/❌</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>No rejected ads</td>
<td>✅/❌</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>Spend normal</td>
<td>✅/❌</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td>No policy update notifications</td>
<td>✅/❌</td>
<td></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
<h2>3. Weekly Inspection (30 Minutes)</h2>
<h3>Step 4: Deep Creative Review</h3>
<p>Beyond platform-rejected ads, manually sample-check running creatives:</p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Copy compliance</strong>: No absolute claims ("best," "#1"), false promotional info</li>
<li><strong>Landing page consistency</strong>: Ad promises match landing page exactly</li>
<li><strong>Age restriction labeling</strong>: Alcohol, finance, healthcare products have correct age targeting</li>
<li><strong>Copyrighted materials</strong>: Images, music, video with proper licensing</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 5: Check Regional Policies</h3>
<p>Ad policies vary significantly across countries. Weekly confirm:</p>
<ul>
<li>Any changes in local regulations for newly added regions</li>
<li>New restricted industries or keywords</li>
<li>GDPR compliance statements in place for EU regions</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 6: Review Account Permissions</h3>
<p>Check account access configuration:</p>
<ul>
<li>Departed employees' accounts removed</li>
<li>New personnel permissions are appropriate (avoid over-authorization)</li>
<li>Any abnormal login records</li>
</ul>
<h2>4. Monthly Inspection (1 Hour)</h2>
<h3>Step 7: Historical Violation Review</h3>
<p>Compile all monthly violations and analyze:</p>
<ul>
<li>Which violation types appear most frequently</li>
<li>Common problem patterns (e.g., certain creative styles repeatedly rejected)</li>
<li>Whether violations cluster around specific platforms or accounts</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 8: Competitor Compliance Research</h3>
<p>Observe competitors' advertising:</p>
<ul>
<li>Their creative directions and copy styles</li>
<li>Platform审核 standards for similar categories</li>
<li>New compliance benchmarks for reference</li>
</ul>
<h3>Step 9: Team Training and Process Optimization</h3>
<p>Based on monthly inspection results:</p>
<ul>
<li>Update internal creative review checklists</li>
<li>Conduct brief compliance training (15-30 minutes)</li>
<li>Optimize impractical SOP steps</li>
</ul>
<h2>5. Quick Handling of Common Violations</h2>
<h3>Ad Rejected Without Clear Reason</h3>
<ol>
<li>Search error codes in platform help center</li>
<li>Contact platform support for specific policy explanations</li>
<li>Screenshot and save communication records in violation log</li>
</ol>
<h3>Account Suddenly Restricted</h3>
<ol>
<li>Don't repeatedly try creating new ads (may worsen penalties)</li>
<li>Submit appeal through official channels with explanation</li>
<li>Check other platform accounts for similar issues</li>
</ol>
<h3>Local Regulation Complaints</h3>
<ol>
<li>Immediately pause related ads</li>
<li>Consult legal team for risk assessment</li>
<li>Respond actively to consumer complaints</li>
</ol>
<h2>Final Thoughts</h2>
<p>The essence of compliance inspection isn't "plugging holes" but building sustainable risk awareness. Execution rhythms vary by team, but consistency is key: <strong>inspect regularly, review periodically, and iterate continuously</strong>.</p>
<p>If you encounter specific compliance issues during execution, feel free to contact us for targeted diagnostic advice.</p>
